An ''[[inversion (discrete mathematics)|inversion]]'' of a permutation&amp;nbsp;''σ'' is a pair {{nowrap|(''i'',''j'')}} of positions where the entries of a permutation are in the opposite order: {{nowrap|''i'' &lt; ''j''}} and {{nowrap|''σ_i'' &gt; ''σ_j''}}.{{sfn|Bóna|2004|p=43}}  So a descent is just an inversion at two adjacent positions. For example, the permutation {{nowrap|''σ'' {{=}} 23154}} has three inversions: (1,3), (2,3), (4,5), for the pairs of entries (2,1), (3,1), (5,4).
